}}'''Oba Shrine'' (Oba Shrine) is {{ill|lt=extension (era name)|Q1327274|WD=Q1327274|lt=Extended|1=Enchō}} {{jalink|Sagami Province|Q105 described in "{{ill|lt=Engishiki Shinmyocho|Q11064932|WD=Q11064932|1=Engishiki Jinmyōchō}}" in 5 years ({{ill|lt=927|Q30470|WD=Q30470|1=927}}) 3732}} is one (small shrine) of the {{ill|lt=List of Shikinaisha in Sagami Province|Q11582137|WD=Q11582137|lt=13 Shikinaisha in Engi|1=List of Shikinaisha in Sagami Province}}, but there are two {{ill|lt=Ronsha|Q135022904|WD=Q135022904|1=Shikinai Ronsha}} (Hijosha). The distance between the two companies is relatively close at approximately 1.5{{ill|lt=kilometer|Q828224|WD=Q828224|lt=km|1=Kilometre}} (about 20 minutes walk). Both companies are listed in this section.

=== Oba Shrine (Inari, Fujisawa City) ===
'''Oba Shrine'' is located near the border with {{ill|lt=Kanagawa Prefecture|Q127513|WD=Q127513|1=Kanagawa Prefecture}}{{ill|lt=Fujisawa City|Q386661|WD=Q386661|1=Fujisawa, Kanagawa}} Inari <ref group="notes">{{ill|lt=Oba (Fujisawa City)|Q11435364|WD=Q11435364|lt=Oba|1=Ōba}}. It is {{ill|lt=Shrine|Q845945|WD=Q845945|1=Shinto shrine}} that is enshrined in </ref>. Located on {{ill|lt=hills|Q222912|WD=Q222912|1=Hügelland}} along {{ill|lt=Hikiji River|Q11487144|WD=Q11487144|1=Hikiji River}}. In the {{ill|lt=Edo period|Q184963|WD=Q184963|1=Edo period}}, it was called "Tenjingu," "Oba Daimyojin," and "Oba Tenmangu." Oba Shrine] (Investigation of Engishiki Shrine)</ref>.

=== Enshrined God ===
* '''{{ill|WD=Q3275901|lt=Kamimusubi|UNKNOWN|lt=Shinnobureishin|1=Kamimusubi}}''' ({{ill|lt=Enshrined Deity#Main Deity/Augami|Q11591100|WD=Q11591100|lt=Main Enshrined Deity|1=Saijin}})
* {{ill|lt=Michizane Sugawara|Q382005|WD=Q382005|lt=Michizane Sugawara|1=Sugawara no Michizane}}
* {{ill|lt=Kagechika Oba|Q1155414|WD=Q1155414|lt=Kagechika Saburo Oba|1=Ōba Kagechika}}

=== History ===
Although "Engishiki Jinmyocho" compiled in the {{ill|lt=Heian period|Q193292|WD=Q193292|1=Heian period}} mentions "{{ill|lt=Koza District|Q1202776|WD=Q1202776|1=Kōza District, Kanagawa}} Oba Shrine," there are no other records (shaden) prior to {{ill|lt=Early modern times|Q5308718|WD=Q5308718|1=Early modern period}}. The information board in the precincts about our company's history says, ``It was ranked as one of the 13 Sagami shrines and is a small shrine, and this place has been passed down as an old place since ancient times.'' "Sagami 13-no-Ichi Nishite-kosha 2 rows of Serarere are the old folklore of ancient places"</ref>.

The {{ill|lt=Bōshu bell|Q8192099|WD=Q8192099|1=Bonshō}} in the temple grounds was built in {{ill|lt=Kyoho|Q1145048|WD=Q1145048|1=Kyōhō}}6 ({{ill|lt=1721|Q6913|WD=Q6913|1=1721}}). alink|casting|Q496098}}, and it is said that the words ``Tenmatenjingu'' were originally written on it, but these words were scratched off and the words ``Oba Daimyojin'' were carved into it. Also, according to "Fujisawa Cultural Properties" published by the {{ill|lt=Board of Education|Q399541|WD=Q399541|1=Board of education}} of Fujisawa City, our company was called "Tenjin Shrine" before {{ill|lt=Meiji|Q3125096|WD=Q3125096|1=Meiji era}}<ref name="shonan-mark">[http://pub.ne.jp/karihomaru/?entry_id=3609822 Two Oba Shrines] (Shonan Mark's room)</ref>.{{ill|lt=Yasunaga (era name)|Q1193910|WD=Q1193910|lt=Yasunaga|1=An'ei}}6 ({{ill|lt=1777|Q7709|WD=Q7709|1=1777}}), King Shien of Jingi acquired Saburo Kagechika Oba, who was based in {{ill|lt=Oba Castle|Q11435376|WD=Q11435376|1=Oba Castle}}, and {{ill|UNKNOWN|lt=Tenmei|1=UNKNOWN}}3 ({{ill|lt=1783|Q7745|WD=Q7745|1=1783}}), Michima Sugawara was {{ill|UNKNOWN|lt=enshrined|1=UNKNOWN}} ({{ill|lt=enshrined|Q11412524|WD=Q11412524|1=Co-Enshrinement}}) according to the wishes of Suwabe Sadaro, Yamazaki Rokurobei Kanataka, and others. Before the Meiji era {{ill|UNKNOWN|lt=Ordinance on the Separation of Shinto and Buddhism|1=UNKNOWN}}, {{ill|lt=Jōjuin (Fujisawa City)|Q18337056|WD=Q18337056|lt=Jōjuin|1=Jōjuin}}, located behind our company, was managing our company as {{ill|lt=Bettoji|Q11396755|WD=Q11396755|1=Bettō-ji}}<ref name="chosa1" />.

