=== Kumano Shrine (Oba, Fujisawa City) ===
{{Shrine
|Name = Kumano Shrine
|Image= [[File:OOBA-Jinjya-kuma03.JPG|250px]]<br />Oratory<br />{{maplink2|frame=yes|plain=yes|type=point|marker=religious-shinto|zoom=14|frame-align=center|frame-width=250|coord={{coord|35|21|15.9|N|139|27|6.7|E}}}}
|Location = 1846 Oba, Fujisawa City, Kanagawa Prefecture
|Position = {{Wiki coordinates 2 steps degrees minutes seconds|35|21|15.9|N|139|27|6.7|E|scale:5000|name=Kumano Shrine (Oba Shrine)}}
|Enshrined deity = Kumano Kusuhi no Mikoto
|Shakaku = Shikinaisha (small)
|Foundation = unknown
|Main shrine =
|Alias = Gongen-sama
|Regular festival = September 9th
|Map = {{Location map|Japan Kanagawa|label=Kumano Shrine|coordinates=
{{coord2|35|21|15.9|N|139|27|6.7|E|}}|position=bottom|width=200|mark=Shinto torii icon vermillion.svg|marksize=15|float=center|caption=}}
}}[]
``Kumano Shrine'' is a shrine located in Fujisawa City, Kanagawa Prefecture {{ill|lt=Oba (Fujisawa City)|Q11435364|WD=Q11435364|lt=Oba|1=Ōba}}. In the Edo period, it was called ``Goryosha'' and ``Gongensha,'' but stone monuments and information boards in the precincts say ``Oba Shrine 舊达''. </ref>, or "Oba Shrine Historic Site" <ref name="chosa2">[https://web.archive.org/web/20151130003000/http://www.geocities.jp/engisiki/sagami/bun/sag160501-02.html Kumano Shrine] (Survey of Engishiki Shrines)</ref>.

=== Enshrined God ===
* '''Kumano Kusuhime'''

=== Historic site of Oba Shrine and Obago ===
This area is said to be the historic site of Oba Shrine. From the hilly area in front of this area, you can see {{ill|lt=earthenware|Q1377111|WD=Q1377111|1=Earthenware}} from the early {{ill|lt=Jomon period|Q52824|WD=Q52824|1=Jōmon period}} period, {{ill|lt=Yayoi period|Q207858|WD=Q207858|1=Yayoi period}}, and {{jalin} k|Nara Period|Q189178}} Remains of residences have been found ({{ill|UNKNOWN|lt=Oba Tsukiyama Ruins|1=UNKNOWN}}), and it is assumed that the {{ill|lt=village|Q486972|WD=Q486972|1=Human settlement}} of Oba-go was formed from ancient times.<ref name="chosa2" />.

=== History ===
Similar to Oba Shrine, an Inari shrine in the same city (see {{ill|lt=#Oba Shrine (Fujisawa City Inari)|UNKNOWN|lt=previous section}}), there are no records (shrine biographies) from before modern times.

It was during the Edo period that our company became the historic site of Oba Shrine (Oba Shrine). name="chosa2" />. The aforementioned ``Fujisawa Cultural Properties'' discusses that our company was originally ``Oba Shrine,'' an Engishiki shrine, but that for some reason, Oba Shrine in Inari came to be regarded as an Engishiki shrine <ref name="shonan-mark" />.

On the other hand, it is also said that it was {{ill|lt=Bunsha|Q195793|WD=Q195793|1=Bunrei}} ({{ill|lt=Bunsha|Q18989808|WD=Q18989808|1=Bunsha}}) from {{ill|lt=Goryo Shrine (Miyamae, Fujisawa City)|Q20044399|WD=Q20044399|lt=Goryo Shrine|1=Goryō Shrine (Miyamae, Fujisawa)}} located in Miyamae, Fujisawa City.

In {{ill|lt=Tenpo|Q1369045|WD=Q1369045|1=Tenpō}}4 ({{ill|lt=1833|Q7587|WD=Q7587|1=1833}}), a stone torii gate was donated by Rokubei Masahiko Yamazaki. Furthermore, this shrine was also managed by Joju-in until the Meiji era's ordinance separating Shinto and Buddhism<ref name="chosa2" />.

